@startuml C4_Concern_Caching
!include https://raw.githubusercontent.com/plantuml-stdlib/C4-PlantUML/master/C4_Component.puml

title YAWL Cross-Cutting Concern - Caching Strategy

Boundary(cache_levels, "Multi-Level Cache") {
    Component(l1, "L1 Cache (JVM Heap)", "Fast", "Request-scoped")
    Component(l2, "L2 Cache (Redis)", "Warm", "Process-scoped (5-30min)")
    Component(l3, "L3 Cache (CDN)", "Global", "Shared (1hr+)")
}

Boundary(cache_patterns, "Caching Patterns") {
    Component(cache_aside, "Cache-Aside", "Pattern", "Client loads")
    Component(write_through, "Write-Through", "Pattern", "All writes to cache")
    Component(write_behind, "Write-Behind", "Pattern", "Async persistence")
}

Boundary(invalidation, "Invalidation Strategy") {
    Component(ttl, "TTL-Based", "Simple", "Time-based expiry")
    Component(event_based, "Event-Based", "Smart", "Invalidate on change")
    Component(version_based, "Version-Based", "Versioning", "Version increment")
}

Boundary(metrics, "Cache Metrics") {
    Component(hit_rate, "Hit Rate", "Target", ">80%")
    Component(eviction_rate, "EvictionRate", "Monitor", "<10%")
    Component(latency, "Latency", "Target", "<10ms")
}

l1 --> l2: Spills to
l2 --> l3: Spills to
cache_aside --> l1: Loads into
write_through --> l2: Writes to
write_behind --> l2: Queues to

ttl --> l1: Expires
event_based --> l2: Invalidates on event
version_based --> l3: Versioned keys

Note as N1
Multi-Level Cache Strategy:

L1 Cache (JVM Heap):
- Hotspot data (permissions, config)
- Scope: Per-request
- TTL: <1 second
- Size: Limited (heap pressure)

L2 Cache (Redis):
- Frequently accessed (users, workflows)
- Scope: Per-process (5-30 min)
- TTL: 5-30 minutes
- Replication: Distributed

L3 Cache (CDN):
- Static assets (images, CSS)
- Scope: Global (1hr+)
- TTL: 1 hour to 1 day
- Edge caching

Caching Patterns:

Cache-Aside (Most common):
1. Check cache for data
2. If hit: return from cache
3. If miss: load from DB
4. Store in cache
5. Return data

Write-Through:
1. Write to cache
2. Write to DB (synchronous)
3. Return to client
Pro: Data consistency
Con: Slower writes

Write-Behind (Async):
1. Write to cache
2. Queue write to DB (async)
3. Return to client immediately
Pro: Fast writes
Con: Possible data loss

Invalidation:

TTL (Time To Live):
- Simple: Expire after N seconds
- Trade-off: Stale data or low TTL

Event-Based:
- On data change: broadcast invalidation
- Pro: Always fresh
- Con: Complex coordination

Version-Based:
- Key format: "resource#v1", "resource#v2"
- New version = new key
- Pro: No invalidation overhead
- Con: Orphaned keys

Metrics:

Cache Hit Rate (Target: >80%):
- High = good caching strategy
- Low = need better key design

Eviction Rate (Target: <10%):
- Too high = cache too small
- Monitor memory pressure

Latency (Target: <10ms):
- L1: <1ms
- L2: <5ms
- L3: <10ms
End note

SHOW_LEGEND()
@enduml
